            {
               "text": "### Images from San Jose CR Museo\n\nThese images are copyright for San Jose CR Museo and allowed to be used according to the license determined by them.\n\nTo visualize all images, use the left and right arrows on the slide below.",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><div class=\"htSlides\"><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">1 / 2</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"img0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img0', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Map of the \"world\" © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite0>). Shared under the <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a>.</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Atlas: Comparing Worlds - Comparison between the world understood by the Babylonians and our current world. (<htcite2>)</li><li>Atlas: The Ancient Babylonian World Map - Babylon: Study of the first known world map. (<htcite3>)</li><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Part I) - While humanity originated in Africa, the first civilizations emerged in various regions around the world, such as Mesopotamia, the Andes, and Mesoamerica. (<htcite4>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Anachronism - although it is a word unknown to many, it is an action frequently practiced. (<htcite5>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Equality Levels - Some concepts, like the definition of a planet, change over time. Sometimes, objects with slightly different sizes can be considered equal. How can we use numbers to quantify equality? (<htcite6>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Did texts written in Mesopotamia describe the world we know today? (<htcite7>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? (<htcite7>)</li></ul></div></div><div class=\"htSlide\"><div class=\"htSlideCounter\">2 / 2</div><img class=\"imgGameSize\" id=\"img0\" onclick=\"htImageZoom('img0', '0%')\"><div class=\"htSlideCaption\">Map of the \"world\" © Trustees of the British Museum (<htcite1>). Shared under the <a href=\"https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0/\" target=\"_blank\">Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial-ShareAlike 4.0 International (CC BY-NC-SA 4.0)</a>.</div><div class=\"htSlideRefs\"><b>Related content:</b><ul><li>Atlas: Comparing Worlds - Comparison between the world understood by the Babylonians and our current world. (<htcite2>)</li><li>Atlas: The Ancient Babylonian World Map - Babylon: Study of the first known world map. (<htcite3>)</li><li>History: Cradles of civilization (Part I) - While humanity originated in Africa, the first civilizations emerged in various regions around the world, such as Mesopotamia, the Andes, and Mesoamerica. (<htcite4>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Anachronism - although it is a word unknown to many, it is an action frequently practiced. (<htcite5>)</li><li>Understanding Texts: Equality Levels - Some concepts, like the definition of a planet, change over time. Sometimes, objects with slightly different sizes can be considered equal. How can we use numbers to quantify equality? (<htcite6>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Did texts written in Mesopotamia describe the world we know today? (<htcite7>)</li><li>Myths and Believes: Has there never been a flood? (<htcite7>)</li></ul></div></div><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-left htSlidePrev\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(-1);\"></i><i class=\"fa-solid fa-chevron-right htSlideNext\" onclick=\"htPlusDivs(1);\"></i></div></p>",
